{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412820"},"attributes":{"position":2,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:41:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:41:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261079"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261079"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19466"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:09:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:09:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19466"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261079"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T08:44:36+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":4,"questionsAnswered":3,"marksTotal":4,"marksAttainable":3,"marksAttempted":3,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:41:39+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"19466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19466"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.15,0.59,0.02,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111169"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12193"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"358"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1698"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41756"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111169"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of progressive perineal pain, fever and general unwellness. She was initially treated by her General Practitioner with oral cefalexin for cellulitis. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has a BMI of 45 kg/m\u00b2 and smokes 15 cigarettes per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. There is a 10 x 10 cm area of induration over her left perineum with surrounding cellulitis. The area is very tender to touch with crepitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal a white cell count of 12 x 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0) and C-reactive protein 300 mg/L (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the microbiology of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monomicrobial gram-positive infection","Monomicrobial gram-negative infection","Polymicrobial infection","Fungal infection","Anaerobic infection alone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with Fournier\u0027s gangrene, a rapidly progressive necrotising fasciitis of the perineal, genital and perianal regions. The presence of crepitation suggests gas-forming organisms, and the clinical deterioration despite antibiotic therapy indicates a severe soft tissue infection requiring urgent surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymicrobial infection\u003C/strong\u003E is the hallmark of Fournier\u0027s gangrene. The condition typically involves a synergistic combination of aerobic and anaerobic bacteria. Common aerobic organisms include \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EProteus\u003C/em\u003E species, while anaerobic bacteria often include \u003Cem\u003EBacteroides\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EClostridium\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EPeptostreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species. Streptococci and enterococci are also frequently isolated. This polymicrobial synergy leads to rapid tissue destruction through combined enzymatic degradation and vascular thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonomicrobial gram-positive infection\u003C/strong\u003E is uncommon in Fournier\u0027s gangrene. While gram-positive organisms like streptococci may be present, they rarely act alone in this condition. Simple cellulitis might be caused by a single gram-positive organism, but the severity and crepitation in this case suggest a more complex infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonomicrobial gram-negative infection\u003C/strong\u003E similarly does not account for the typical presentation of Fournier\u0027s gangrene. While gram-negative organisms are important contributors, they work in concert with other bacteria rather than in isolation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFungal infection\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary cause of Fournier\u0027s gangrene, though fungal superinfection may occasionally occur in immunocompromised patients or following prolonged antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaerobic infection alone\u003C/strong\u003E does not cause Fournier\u0027s gangrene. While anaerobes play a crucial role in the pathogenesis, they work synergistically with aerobic bacteria. The gas production seen as crepitation is often from anaerobes, but the tissue destruction requires the combined action of multiple organism types.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe polymicrobial nature of Fournier\u0027s gangrene has important treatment implications, requiring broad-spectrum antibiotic coverage (e.g., meropenem, clindamycin, and vancomycin) alongside urgent surgical debridement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fournier\u0027s gangrene is typically caused by polymicrobial infection involving aerobic and anaerobic bacteria.","Common organisms include Escherichia coli, Bacteroides, streptococci, and enterococci working synergistically.","The polymicrobial nature necessitates broad-spectrum antibiotic coverage alongside urgent surgical debridement."],"references":["Stevens DL, Bryant AE. Necrotizing Soft-Tissue Infections. N Engl J Med. 2017 Dec 7;377(23):2253-2265. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1600673. PMID: 29211672."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19466"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T20:19:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T20:19:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12193"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111169"}}},